Héma-Québec yesterday celebrated its 10th anniversary of its founding, and its president, Francine Décary, had reason to rejoice, because Héma-Québec has once again become one of the safest and most efficient providers of blood in the world. 
And above all, reconquered the confidence of the public who had been seriously faltered for the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s. 
As is known, the reserves managed by national blood transfusion service of the Canadian Red Cross have been contaminated by the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and hepatitis C during the 1980s. 
Faced with this tragedy and to the dissatisfaction of the public, the government of Canada made in February 1994 a public inquiry, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, who sought to clarify the circumstances that had led to this tragedy and make recommendations for such a disaster is not play more. 
While the judge Krever took to submit their relationship, certain provinces then created a committee that was aimed at planning a new system of management of the blood in Canada. 
In Quebec, the committee Gélineau fulfilled this mission. 
As a result of reports of Gélineau and Krever, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Héma-Québec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Society of blood supply to all other provinces and two territories. 
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec began operations, almost 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, recalls Décary. 
The situation was grim. 
Having made many efforts to improve the safety of blood products and a lot of work over the years that followed, we have regained the confidence of the public, "he says before assert proudly that at the beginning of 2008, approximately 94% of the population Quebec hereinafter had confidence in Héma-Québec. 
Dr. Décary reminded however that "confidence is extremely fragile." 
Since its inception, the Sept. 28, 1998, Héma-Québec applied the precautionary principle. 
At that time, in Europe attended the birth of numerous cases of the human variant of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, has Décary. 
And we did not know if this disease could be transmitted through blood. 
So we rely on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, which we do not know where and when a serious illness may stem from that, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease which is characterized by degeneration of brain that leads inevitably to death, established measures of exclusion. 
In April 1999, for refusing the blood of people who had been over a month in the UK since 1980. 
But a few years ago, has been proved beyond all doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood. 
This episode showed us so that the precautionary principle that was applied was the end. " 
In 1999 appeared on the market much more sensitive technique for detecting HIV tests that detect nuclide acid in the blood directly from donors the presence of the virus and not antibodies against the virus, which grounded the tests used until now. 
The evidence of acid nuclide helped shorten the period between the time the person has been infected and the time that the first virus can be detected in blood by our techniques, says the specialist. 
We were able to reduce this period lasting less than a week. 
Thus reducing substantially the risk that some donors may be infected without knowing it and that we can not detectable. 
These improvements helped significantly lower the risk of contracting HIV by a blood transfusion. 
Today, one person every 12 million are at risk of receiving blood contaminated with HIV. 
"That means it will have to distribute 12 million blood products before someone is infected with HIV. 
So since Héma-Quebec distributing each year between 400 000 and 500 000 blood products, will spend more than 24 years before that there occurs a case of transmission of HIV through a blood product. 
I think you can now receive or require a blood transfusion to recover without health concerns, "said the head of the direction of Héma-Québec. 
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products. 
I never know which pathogen could emerge in the system. 
Last year appeared on the island of Reunion that the Chikungunya virus, following the example of West Nile virus is transmitted by an insect in the blood. 
You have to be constantly vigilant, "pursued Dr. Décary before emphasize that in addition to a secure supply, Héma-Québec must also provide adequate supplies. 
"The needs are increasing as the population ages. 
As the most aggressive cancer treatments, patients often need an infusion of red blood cells or platelets. 
The aging population also has consequences on the network of blood donors covering an average of only 3% of Quebeckers are eligible for blood donation. " 
All people with good health, 18 years and that relate to the eligibility criteria can nevertheless give blood every 56 days, or six times a year. 
On average, 14% of those who propose their blood are not accepted, because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they traveled in a country where there is malaria, will be excluded for a period of one year. 
"With this 3%, we succeeded in maintaining an inventory that covers the needs of hospitals. 
The hardships are very rare. 
But we have to renew to the members of this network of donors as they age and can only donate their blood. 
But it is hard to convince people to donate their blood, but above all, retain and encourage them to become regular donors. 
Because life today is very rampant, rarely find the time to spend an hour to donate their blood, "Francine Décary was distressed. 
With a budget of 297 million dollars a year, Héma-Québec caters not only blood products, but also human tissues, including the bone grafts, heart valves, skin and eyeballs that is almost exclusively used for major burns. 
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Quebec, which also operates the only public bank of umbilical cord blood in Quebec. 
The umbilical cord that formerly was regarded as biomedical waste is filled with a rich blood stem cells that can be used for treatment of serious diseases like leukemia. 
"We have had a few weeks ago, putting on the bank of our thousandth sample of umbilical cord blood and is expected to draw over a thousand of these a year. 
We should begin to propose to graft at the beginning of next year, "explains Dr. Décary describing this program takes cord blood as very popular. 
