Psychology of overlap: Why spend more money? 
The participants of the auctions are likely to spend more money and overestimate the product. 
Neuroscientists and economists from the University of New York discovered the neurological basis - this economic well-known and seemingly irrational behavior. 
According to the study published in the journal Science, people do not want to lose in competitions such as auctions on eBay, why even prefer to pay a price too high. 
The scientists attempted to outline the neurological impact of this "game" by means of experimental auctions. 
One group of volunteers playing lottery, the other was involved in an auction and meanwhile discussed by the system of functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) active areas of the brain of people involved in the experiment. 
In both games the participants could make money, but at the auction, which is a key element to bet more than the other, to lose the game became more intense operation of the complex called stratum located below the cerebral cortex. 
This area of the brain, plus many other roles, plays a role in the mechanism of "auto prize" of the nervous system. 
So according to scientists, raising the stakes are explained as a prevention so as not to cause an intense reaction of the stratum. 
To substantiate his theory, economists scientific group also conducted a study of financial monitoring. 
In this experiment, three groups bet on a person under different circumstances. 
The control group were simply told the real value of the product in question and its members bet. 
On top of that another group was promised that if they win, would receive more than 15 U.S. dollars prize. 
In contrast, the third group received just 15 U.S. dollars before the auction, but in case of losing the auction, the group lost even that money. 
So the only difference between the two groups was that a victory was highlighted and the other for the failure. 
However, proving the hypothesis of neurologists, members of the group playing "against failure" were willing to bet even more that members of the control group and the group "winner". 
"These results can not be deducted from any previously existing economic theory. 
Because those so far explained the phenomena of the auctions only with the joy of winning and to the prevention of risks. 
Only neurological visual methods helped to resolve this contradiction between the two theories, so now we come to a third explanation "- established Andrew Schott, a professor at the faculty of economics at the University of New York. 
