In the world some five million people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary the chronic disease of the liver is considered one of the leading causes of death. 
An estimated one hundred thousand the number of infected in this country, but only seven thousand receiving treatment since many patients do not know they are infected. 
The designation of hepatitis is the common name for different Liver disease caused by viruses. 
The symptoms are very similar, are characteristic infection of the liver and jaundice, but their pathogens and the diseases are quite distinct. 
The virus of hepatitis depending on the pathogen spread through two main forms: hepatitis A and E via food (for example with infected water or food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses in the blood and moods Corporal (semen, humor of the vagina, saliva). 
It is recommended for travelers to protect vaccine virus A and B, against C vaccines do not exist. 
Symptoms of hepatitis A by two or three weeks after consuming the infected food, is manifested through a generally poor condition, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea. 
After that appear on the skin and the whites of the eyes jaundice, the stool becomes clear, dark urine and healing can last even two - three weeks. 
Annually one million people died worldwide in cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B, the most serious forms of this disease. 
The main reason for this is that according to estimates, only one in ten infected receive drug treatment. 
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: untreated can cause cirrhosis and liver cancer. 
Most of those infected do not know who is sick because this pathological agent in gradually destroys cells in the liver and often the first symptoms appear only after 20-30 years. 
Therefore it is very important to the premature recognition, the medical routine. 
It is much more common disease in three groups: people who had blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and those with tattoos. 
There are currently some 200 million people worldwide who suffer from chronic hepatitis C. 
As this disease can be discovered by a routine control laboratory is also worth consulting with the doctor of the family to experience any symptoms unknown. 
The disease is cured if discovered in time, it is possible to exterminate the virus in the body and can suppress the infection and prevent cancer. 
On September 30 is World Day of Hepatitis, which was first organized in 2004 by organizations representing patients. 
Its aim is to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by viruses and the importance of its premature recognition. 
